  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Maintain detailed customer records\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting\n- Identify and report unusual transactions\n- File suspicious activity reports (SARs)\n- Monitor transactions for potential money laundering\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Train employees on detecting potential money laundering\n- Implement transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Record keeping\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Retain documentation for specified periods\n- Ensure records are available for regulatory review\n\n5. Risk assessment\n- Evaluate customer and transaction risks\n- Implement enhanced due diligence for high-risk accounts\n- Regularly update risk assessment protocols\n\n6. Regulatory compliance\n- Follow laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Comply with international anti-money laundering standards\n- Submit required reports to regulatory authorities\n\nFailing to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.",
